article.headline: Knights end Seahawks' spirited run through tourney
article.linkText: Fairleigh Dickinson dancing with Northeast title
article.story: HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) -- A late 3-pointer by Mensah Peterson and 29 points from two players who were scoreless in the previous game has Fairleigh Dickinson in the NCAA Tournament for the first time since 1998. "I think the whole team played well," Peterson said after the second-seeded Knights defeated Wagner 58-52 to win the Northeast Conference tournament on Wednesday night. "We all had to step up," Peterson added. "It's all about wanting to win. It's a great feeling that we won. I still can't believe it's happening. I don't care who we play. It doesn't matter at this point. We're in. That's all that matters." Fairleigh Dickinson (20-12) had a lot of contributors in preventing Wagner (13-17) from becoming only the second sixth seed to win the conference tournament. Italian center Andrea Crosariol, who had only two points in the first two games of the tournament, scored 18 points, two shy of his career best. "After [the] last game, I had to prove that I was a basketball player," said Crosariol, who didn't score in the conference semifinal. "I didn't feel that way the other night. I feel like I gave the team the lift we needed to play good." Chad Timberlake, who also was blanked in the semifinal win over Long Island University on Sunday, had 11 points. Peterson scored seven of his 13 points in the final 3:28, including a 3-pointer with 23.8 seconds to play that gave Fairleigh Dickinson a 56-50 lead and iced coach Tom Green's fourth trip to the NCAAs in his 22-year career. Durell Vinson had 14 points and eight rebounds for Wagner, which was trying to cap an amazing turnaround after a 2-15 start. The loss was only its second in 13 games. "I think what we accomplished this season down the stretch has been truly remarkable," said Wagner coach Mike Deane, who failed in his bid to become the fifth coach to take four different schools to the NCAA tournament. "The fact we came up short is disappointing. It doesn't change what we've done. I proud of our guys." The Seahawks nearly staged a final comeback after falling behind 47-36 on a 3-pointer by Gordon Klaiber with 10:31 to play. The Knights did not score another field goal until Peterson hit his big 3 in the final minute. Mark Porter, who led Wagner to its upset of top-seeded Monmouth on Sunday, keyed the 13-4 spurt with eight points. His two free throws cut the lead to 51-49 with 1:23 remaining. Peterson was fouled 12 seconds later and hit both ends of a one-and-one opportunity to push the lead to 53-49. Porter hit one free throw with 56 seconds to go to cut the lead to three. Wagner elected to defend on the Knights' next possession and Peterson made them pay with a 20-footer with 2 seconds left on the shot clock. "Chad [Timberlake] drove the middle of the lane and kicked it back to me," Peterson said. "It was a good pass and I just shot the ball. I was surprised how much they left me open. It felt real good leaving my hands." By the time the final horn sounded, the fans were already on the floor celebrating. Sean Munson, the Seahawks' leading scorer and rebounder, struggled in his return to the lineup, scoring eight points on 2-of-12 shooting. The senior center played only 3 minutes in the tournament semifinals after developing back spasms. He averaged 17.5 points and 12 rebounds in the two regular season games against Fairleigh Dickinson. "It was bothering me, it was definitely bothering me," said Munson, who had four rebounds in 21 minutes. Despite shooting 28.1 percent from the field and having Munson go 1-for-9, the Seahawks only trailed 28-24 at the half. Fairleigh Dickinson took the lead for good with a 14-2 run that featured seven points from Crosariol, who was averaging 7.5 points. He finished 7-of-10 from the field, with the seven field goals being one more than he had in his last five games combined. The Knights pushed the lead to 11 points with a 9-2 spurt that featured four by Timberlake.
